<h2>Conquer Héngshān Mountain</h2>
<p>Hengshan (traditional Chinese: 恆山; simplified: 恒山; pinyin: Héng Shān) also known as Yuanyue or Changshan, located in Hunyuan district, Shanxi province, China, is a mountain in the "Five Mountains". , so it is also called Bac Nhac. The highest peak of Hang Son is Thien Phong Linh with a height of 2,016.1m[1], the main temple is Bac Nhac temple, worshiping the god Hang Son (Bac Nhac the Great). Legend has it that King Shun, when he came here to patrol his beasts, named Hang Son the name Bac Nhac. According to Taoism, one of the eight immortals, Truong Qua Lao, also practiced immortality here, and finally, at the top of Hang Son, he rode a feather to the sky. <br> <br>

    From the beginning of the Western Han period, Hang Son had temples and pagodas; By the Ming and Qing dynasties, pagodas and temples were quite crowded, with "three pagodas, four temples, nine pavilion, seven palaces, eight caves, twelve temples" (three pagodas, four temples, nine pavilion, seven palaces). , eight caves, twelve temples). The Hang Son landscape is both majestic and dangerous with strange pagodas and beautiful streams, recorded by Tu Ha Khach (1587-1641) during the Ming Dynasty in Tu Ha Khach's Travels. In ancient times, Hang Son had up to 18 landscapes, today there still exist the Imperial Palace, Hoi Tien Palace, Cuu Thien Palace, Kim Long Khau and Huyen Khong pagoda. Huyen Khong Pagoda is about 3 km from the mouth of Hang Son mountain, built around the end of the Northern Wei period with unique architecture, which can be generalized as "strange, mysterious, cunning".</p>
